gland":"Buckinghamshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"–1350":"–1350","1311–1388":"1311–1388","1272–1350":"1272–1350","1334–1388":"1334–1388","1335–Male":"1335–Deceased","1336–Male":"1336–Deceased","1337–1413":"1337–1413","1280–1388":"1280–1388","1285–Female":"1285–Deceased","1285":"1285","Abt 1335":"about 1335","1350":"1350","1272":"1272","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1337":"1337","1259":"1259","1413":"1413","1336":"1336","1335":"1335","1334":"1334","1388":"1388","1311":"1311","about 1336":"about 1336","1310":"1310","1453":"1453","about 1337":"about 1337","about 1334":"about 1334","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Echingham, Sussex, England":"Sussex, England, United Kingdom","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England","Hampden, Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Dakeney","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Hackney  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hackney","meanings":["English:","habitational name from Hackney in Greater London, named from an Old English personal name <i>Haca</i> (genitive <i>Hacan</i>) + <i>ēg</i> ‘island, dry ground in marshland’.","perhaps from Middle English <i>hakenei</i> (Old French <i>haquenée</i>), an ambling horse or mare, especially one considered suitable for women to ride; perhaps therefore a metonymic occupational name for a breeder or keeper of such horses and short for <i>Hakeneyman</i>. This surname has also been found in Scotland since medieval times."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":27,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705190,"age":58,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705191,"age":83,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705192,"age":96,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705193,"age":105,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Joan Dakeney was born as the daughter of Roger Dakeney and Joan Cave. She had at least 4 sons with Sir James Echyngham. She died in 1350, in Sussex, England."},"et":{"–1350":"–1350","1311–1388":"1311–1388","1272–1350":"1272–1350","1334–1388":"1334–1388","1335–Male":"1335–Surnud","1336–Male":"1336–Surnud","1337–1413":"1337–1413","1280–1388":"1280–1388","1285–Female":"1285–Surnud","1285":"1285","Abt 1335":"umbes 1335","1350":"1350","1272":"1272","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1337":"1337","1259":"1259","1413":"1413","1336":"1336","1335":"1335","1334":"1334","1388":"1388","1311":"1311","about 1336":"umbes 1336","1310":"1310","1453":"1453","about 1337":"umbes 1337","about 1334":"umbes 1334","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Echingham, Sussex, England":"Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England","Hampden, Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"–1350":"–1350","1311–1388":"1311–1388","1272–1350":"1272–1350","1334–1388":"1334–1388","1335–Male":"1335–Kuollut","1336–Male":"1336–Kuollut","